From: Florian Maurer <fmaurer@disroot.org>
Subject: [PATCH] ARM: smp: call rcutree_report_cpu_dead() in ipi_cpu_stop()

When the system is halted or powered off, machine_halt() and
machine_power_off() use smp_send_stop() to take secondary CPUs offline.
The IPI handler ipi_cpu_stop() clears the dying CPU from cpu_online_mask
via set_cpu_online(cpu, false) and then spins forever in
"cpu_relax(); wfe();" from interrupt context.

This bypasses the normal CPU-hotplug teardown path:
rcutree_report_cpu_dead() and rcutree_offline_cpu() are never called,
so RCU's qsmaskinitnext and ffmask bits for the stopped CPU remain set.
Meanwhile cpu_is_offline() returns true. The two views disagree.

If the RCU grace-period kthread had armed a schedule_timeout() timer on
the stopped CPU just before the IPI arrived, the timer can never be
serviced (the CPU is wedged in IRQ context with IRQs masked), so the
kthread starves until CONFIG_RCU_CPU_STALL_TIMEOUT fires. The stall
detector then kicks the kthread alive on another CPU, where
force_qs_rnp() -> rcu_implicit_dynticks_qs() reaches an
irq_work_queue_on() targeting the offline CPU and trips
WARN_ON_ONCE(cpu_is_offline(cpu)) in kernel/irq_work.c.

Reproduced on Aruba AP-325 (Qualcomm IPQ8068, dual-core Krait) by
issuing "poweroff": 21-second stall followed by the WARN.

Call rcutree_report_cpu_dead() before the wait loop so that RCU's
per-CPU bitmasks match the now-offline state. The function is called on
the stopping CPU itself (it uses this_cpu_ptr internally), and
ipi_cpu_stop() runs from hard-IRQ context with IRQs masked, satisfying
the lockdep_assert_irqs_disabled() inside rcutree_report_cpu_dead().

Signed-off-by: Florian Maurer <fmaurer@disroot.org>
---
 arch/arm/kernel/smp.c | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

--- a/arch/arm/kernel/smp.c
+++ b/arch/arm/kernel/smp.c
@@ -607,6 +607,8 @@ static void ipi_cpu_stop(unsigned int cp

 	set_cpu_online(cpu, false);

+	rcutree_report_cpu_dead();
+
 	while (1) {
 		cpu_relax();
 		wfe();
